Add the token import immediately after `@import "tailwindcss";` in your global CSS, before any other rules. The file installs to `styles/fluent2-tokens.css` at your project root (or `src/styles/fluent2-tokens.css` in a `src` layout), so from `app/globals.css` the import must climb one directory:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@import "../styles/fluent2-tokens.css";
```

The `../` is required because the file lands one level **above** `app/` (at the project root, beside it) â€” a bare `./styles/...` would look inside `app/styles/` and 404. If your global CSS lives directly in `src/` next to `src/styles/` (a common Vite setup with no `app/` folder), drop the `../` and use `@import "./styles/fluent2-tokens.css";` instead.

**If you ran `shadcn init` first:** it seeds your global CSS with its own competing theme (`:root {...}`, `.dark {...}`, `@theme inline {...}`, `@custom-variant dark (...)`, `@layer base`) plus `@import "shadcn/tailwind.css";` and `@import "tw-animate-css";`. Delete all of it â€” those blocks redefine the same variable names and sit after this import in the cascade, so they silently override Fluent's tokens with shadcn's default gray theme. Your global CSS should end up as just the two imports above, nothing more; this file already ships its own `:root`/`.light`/`.dark`/`.high-contrast`, `@theme inline` bridge, `@custom-variant dark`, and `@layer base`.

This file defines `:root` (light, default), `.dark`, `.high-contrast`, and a `@media (forced-colors: active)` layer, plus the Tailwind v4 `@theme inline` bridge that turns every token into a utility class. Toggle dark mode by adding/removing the `dark` class on `<html>` (or another ancestor); toggle high contrast the same way with the `high-contrast` class. No other registry item in this kit depends on `theme`, but every component assumes these tokens are present, so install it first.
